      <bioghist id="aspace_e1ce2101f9a58f121d90f6c610a55bcc">
         <head>Biographical note</head>
         <p>Klemens von Klemperer was a professor of German History at Smtih College from 1949 to 1987. He was a prolific author, publishing eight books and many historical articles. Most of his work concerned German resistance to Hitler during the Nazi regime. He married Smith alumna Elizabeth Gallaher, who taught as a professor of English literature at Smith College.</p>
         <p>Born in Berlin on November 2, 1916, Klemperer was an anti-Nazi activist as a student in Vienna before the rising political tension as well as his family's Jewish background made him flee to the United States in 1938. Upon arriving in the United States, Klemperer pursued his doctorate at Harvard University, where he stayed at Eliot House. His education was interrupted from 1942-1946 when he served as an intelligence officer for the Supreme Headquarters Allied Expeditionary Force (SHAEF), the headquarters of the Allied forces in northwest Europe. Klemperer returned to Hardvard in 1946 and received his doctorate in history in 1949.</p>
         <p>Klemperer was offered a teaching position at Smith College that same year and went on to teach for thirty seven years. Although he retired officially in 1987, Klemperer continued to work in academia, publishing his most acclaimed book in 1992: <italics>German Resistance Against Hitler: the Search for Allies Abroad, 1938-1945</italics>&gt;.</p>
         <p>Klemperer died on December 23, 2012 at his home in Easthampton. His wife Elizabeth would survive him for three years before her death in 2015.</p>  
      </bioghist>
